          "_type": "span",
          "marks": [],
          "text": "Songwriting and Recording"
        }
      ],
      "markDefs": [],
      "style": "h2"
    },
    {
      "_key": "105c6c0cee4c",
      "_type": "block",
      "children": [
        {
          "_key": "9e066feccb02",
          "_type": "span",
          "marks": [],
          "text": "I use Apple Logic Pro for all my recordings. It has a great collection of vintage softsynths. When I used Windows, I favored Sony ACID Pro 7.0 for music composition. It was the best loop-based software I found. While most DAWs today support loops, ACID’s streamlined interface never got in the way of creativity."
        }
      ],
      "markDefs": [],
      "style": "normal"
    },
    {
      "_key": "70ca7af0d5e9",
      "_type": "block",
      "children": [
        {
          "_key": "26ea63f6b7c1",
          "_type": "span",
          "marks": [],
          "text": "I like to write in sections and then arrange those sections into a song. ACID makes this easy because its loop-based approach allows me to record a verse or chorus once and reuse it as many times as I want. You can quickly throw a song together and hear how it will sound. Since I write alone, it’s great to have Mick Fleetwood lay down a drum track and Rudy Sarzo a bass track to inspire me. 😉 Of course, I’m referring to the ability to purchase loops from other musicians and use them in your compositions royalty-free. Usually, when working in a band, someone plays a riff that inspires a jam, which eventually turns into a song. ACID Loops provide that same kind of interactive inspiration."
        }
      ],
      "markDefs": [],
      "style": "normal"
    }
